In TypeScript, you can use type assertions to express that you know a value may have multiple types in theory but in practice will only have one. This can be done using the `assert` keyword with the `oneOf` pattern. Here's how you can do it:

```typescript
interface TypeA {
  value: number;
}

interface TypeB {
  value: string;
}

// Example value that can have either TypeA or TypeB
let value: any;

// Type assertion that the value will only have TypeA in practice
value: oneOf([TypeA, TypeB]) as any;

// Type assertion that the value will only have TypeB in practice
value: oneOf([TypeB]) as any;
```

In this example, the `value` type is declared to be either `TypeA` or `TypeB` in theory. However, by using `oneOf`, you're asserting that in practice, the value will only have one of these types. 

This can be particularly useful in cases where you have a value that can be interpreted in multiple ways, but in actual use, it will only adhere to one specific type.

